<subSubSection id="B88331D9FF9CFF6BB5E63F5F20890526" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F0266252FF9CFF6BB5E63F5F20890526" blockId="6.[136,1452,1055,1298]" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">
In spite of being collected for the first time in 
<collectingCountry id="888E22C2FF9CFF6BB7F93F6022A9040D" box="[663,731,1055,1081]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">Brazil</collectingCountry>
only in 1965 (collection number: Prance 
<emphasis id="C2EDBE40FF9CFF6BB1DB3F5F249C040D" box="[1205,1262,1055,1081]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
1652), 
<bibRefCitation id="94081FA3FF9CFF6BB0283F6020A1046A" author="Bentham, G." pageId="6" pageNumber="195" pagination="226 - 228" refId="ref7178" refString="Bentham, G. (1870) Caesalpinieae. In: von Martius, C. F. P. &amp; Eichler, A. G. (Eds.) Flora Brasiliensis 15 (2). F. Fleischer, Leipzig, pp. 226 - 228." type="book chapter" year="1870">Bentham (1870)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName id="379919D1FF9CFF6BB4233F3B22550469" authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1870" box="[333,551,1091,1117]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Eperua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schomburgkiana">
<emphasis id="C2EDBE40FF9CFF6BB4233F3B22550469" box="[333,551,1091,1117]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">E. schomburgkiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Flora Brasiliensis. He described 
<taxonomicName id="379919D1FF9CFF6BB68A3F3B24CF0469" authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1870" box="[996,1213,1091,1117]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Eperua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schomburgkiana">
<emphasis id="C2EDBE40FF9CFF6BB68A3F3B24CF0469" box="[996,1213,1091,1117]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">E. schomburgkiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a comment on the species 
<taxonomicName id="379919D1FF9CFF6BB5B13F17211704B5" box="[223,357,1128,1153]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Eperua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="C2EDBE40FF9CFF6BB5B13F17211704B5" box="[223,357,1128,1153]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">E. purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, providing a complete diagnosis and pointing that the plant was found in Guyana by Schomburgk. As there were two collections of 
<taxonomicName id="379919D1FF9CFF6BB4953FF322A60491" authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1870" box="[507,724,1163,1189]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Eperua" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="schomburgkiana">
<emphasis id="C2EDBE40FF9CFF6BB4953FF322A60491" box="[507,724,1163,1189]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="195">E. schomburgkiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Schomburgk, 517 and 317, 
<bibRefCitation id="94081FA3FF9CFF6BB15D3FF324A60492" author="Cowan, R. S." box="[1075,1236,1163,1190]" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref7339" refString="Cowan, R. S. (1975) Monograph of the genus Eperua (Leguminosae: Caesalpinioideae). Smithsonian Contributions to Botany 28: 1 - 45. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 0081024 X. 28" type="journal article" year="1975">Cowan (1975)</bibRefCitation>
selected the 517 at K as lectotype and cited the exsiccates at BM, G, K, P, and W as isolectotypes. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="94081FA3FF9CFF6BB10F3FCF257304FE" author="Cowan, R. S." box="[1121,1281,1199,1226]" pageId="6" pageNumber="195" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref7339" refString="Cowan, R. S. (1975) Monograph of the genus Eperua (Leguminosae: Caesalpinioideae). Smithsonian Contributions to Botany 28: 1 - 45. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 0081024 X. 28" type="journal article" year="1975">Cowan (1975)</bibRefCitation>
did not specify which exsiccate refers to the lectotype and isolectotypes at K, which makes the present second-step lectotypification necessary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
